[
    {
        "content": "<p>Technical art uses parameteric equations and scalar fields. Depending on which is easier for the problem to be solved.</p>\n<p>I like to imagine parametric equations as roughly modeling drawing, and scalar fields as roughly modeling painting.</p>\n<p>When you give explicit function signatures, it's clear these concepts are dual.</p>\n<p>There's lots of flexibility in our choices, but a representative example of this duality is</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>↭</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0, 1] \\rightarrow X \\leftrightsquigarrow X \\rightarrow [0, 1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">↭</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>Where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is some topological space. </p>\n<p>In my mind an example of a function on the left can be visualized as a \"drawing\":</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/QRQ55uTLlYlt6UfUtcFjR8pg/c218a217-cb9f-418c-bfc2-e5a94b97e7f8.png\">c218a217-cb9f-418c-bfc2-e5a94b97e7f8.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/QRQ55uTLlYlt6UfUtcFjR8pg/c218a217-cb9f-418c-bfc2-e5a94b97e7f8.png\" title=\"c218a217-cb9f-418c-bfc2-e5a94b97e7f8.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"1280x1280\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/QRQ55uTLlYlt6UfUtcFjR8pg/c218a217-cb9f-418c-bfc2-e5a94b97e7f8.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>And a function on the right can be visualized as a \"painting\":</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/QBUYXl-aVH5fR2pgbcMn-UOF/5224d3a7-01c5-4c62-b67e-ee639be2f6d4.png\">5224d3a7-01c5-4c62-b67e-ee639be2f6d4.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/QBUYXl-aVH5fR2pgbcMn-UOF/5224d3a7-01c5-4c62-b67e-ee639be2f6d4.png\" title=\"5224d3a7-01c5-4c62-b67e-ee639be2f6d4.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"600x600\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/QBUYXl-aVH5fR2pgbcMn-UOF/5224d3a7-01c5-4c62-b67e-ee639be2f6d4.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X = [0, 1]^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> then you'd be drawing or painting on a square paper.</p>\n<p>My intuition, is \"drawings\" and \"paintings\" are related. You can make a map of countries by <em>drawing</em> their borders, or if you have at least four colors you can <em>paint</em> a map of countries.</p>\n<p>Irrespective of my intuition. This duality seems to be really important in category theory. The \"drawings\" correspond to Lawvere's notion of \"figures\", the \"paintings\" correspond to his notion of \"cofigures\".</p>\n<p>They're both examples of representable Functors.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/space+and+quantity\">[[space and quantity]]</a>, if I'm understanding it right, what I call a set of \"paintings\" is a presheaf on topological spaces, or a \"generalized space\".</p>\n<p>And what I call a set of \"drawings\" is a copresheaf, or a generalized quantity.</p>\n<p>Whether you think of these as scalar fields vs parametric functions or \"paintings\" vs \"drawings\", these dual perspectives are clearly closely related, even mutually convertible.</p>\n<p>Where should I start, or what should I think about, to get a better understanding of these categorical definitions and their duality? Are presheafs and copresheafs a good place to start for example?</p>",
        "id": 513137814,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1745041384
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In physics I like to think of a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R} \\rightarrow X </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> as a 'particle' and a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> X \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> as a 'field', where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is 'spacetime'.    Particles and fields give dual ways of thinking about matter.  I'd never noticed that particles are like drawings and fields are like paintings.   Nice!</p>\n<p>A space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1] \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is called a space 'under' <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, and the category of all spaces under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is an example of an 'under category'.</p>\n<p>A space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with a function  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> X \\rightarrow [0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is called a space 'over' <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, and the category of all spaces over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is an example of an 'over category'.</p>\n<p>So one way to learn more is to learn about properties of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/over%20categories\">[[over categories]]</a> (also called 'slice categories') and <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/under%20categories\">[[under categories]]</a> (also called 'coslice categories').</p>\n<p>Lawvere wanted 'spaces', of a very general sort, to be objects of a topos.   Then there's a nice theorem that the over category of any object in a topos is again a topos.  This is often called the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_topos_theory\">fundamental theorem of topos theory</a>.</p>\n<p>It doesn't work like this for under categories!   The under category of an object in a topos is not usually a topos.   So there's a built in asymmetry in the concept of topos (and other aspects of our concepts of space).  If your category of spaces <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a topos, then the category of spaces over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> (spaces <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> equipped with a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to [0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>) is a topos, but the category of spaces under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> (spaces <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0,1] \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>) is usually not.</p>\n<p>So, if you set things up nicely, you can get a topos of paintings, but maybe not a topos of drawings.</p>",
        "id": 513139990,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1745043396
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, if you are willing to discard the requirement that a drawing sits on a pre-existing \"canvas\", then you can get a topos of \"abstract drawings\", namely the topos of (pre)sheaves on the category of \"drawable shapes\".</p>",
        "id": 513141434,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1745044772
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't normally think of a mathematician's chalk line drawings as being more limited than shaded chalk \"paintings\", but ya'll have got me thinking they may be in some subtle way.</p>\n<p>Shulman I'm extremely curious about your comment, but I don't quite understand it. What's the category of \"drawable shapes\"? Did I implicitly define that?</p>",
        "id": 513143127,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1745046262
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is it the under category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[0, 1] \\rightarrow X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 513143226,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1745046362
    },
    {
